{
  "doc_id": "51614",
  "text": "IL-1β is known to stimulate the proliferation of vascular smooth muscle cells and is involved in modifying a number of vascular functions by inducing autocrine production of chemotactic cytokines on endothelial cells, including IL-1β itself [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Moreover, IL-1β has been shown to enhance the production of IL-8 protein, which has been shown to induce angiogenesis in melanoma cells [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . These observations suggest that IL-1β may alter the functional properties of vascular cells, including the induction of angiogenesis. Vascular-biology studies have shown that IL-1β increase VEGF mRNA in rat aortic smooth muscle cells in a timeand dose-dependent manner [CITATION_6] . This induction of VEGF expression was found to be due to an increase in transcription as well as an increase in the stability of its mRNA. However, the role of IL-1β on the induction of VEGF in tumours, specifically human colon cancer, is undefined.",
